Ask HN: How do you manage your personal projects
text:
Recently I've started a personal project that's begun to take up a significant amount of brain space.

It's gotten complicated enough that I've started "dropping" parts of it mentally, and it's hard to find those pieces and pick them back up again.

In my career, I've used every kind of team & project management ware under the sun, and I have a hard time conceiving adapting something like the Asana suite to just my personal workflow.

So, HN - how do you manage your personal projects?

Ask HN: Is Kubernetes Operator the new database stored procedures?
text:
I love the idea of using Kubernetes operators to create and manage a project's infrastructure. Like the PostgreSQL operator or some examples of API gateway operators. But something tells me that this can be a problem. Like in the past, when we used to store logic inside databases, using triggers and stored procedures. And now we know this kind of architecture can lead to problems related to performance, scale, and vendor lock-in.

I know that Kubernetes isn't attached to a single vendor, as we can use it without AWS, Google, or other dependencies. But can we be repeating some error from our past broadly using Operators?

Ask HN: Will AI obliterate small search services? (e.g. DDG, Brave search)
text: While Microsoft and Google press ahead developing AI in their search engines, what will happen to the search engines like DuckDuckGo (DDG) or Brave search, or others? These small, independent, privacy-friendly search services are tiny compared to the tech giants. Will AI obliterate small, independent search services? (Or see their usage drop further?) Can AI be incroporated in other search services?
